Like did King David's men and Jews at that time also have a diluted vinegar-based electrolyte drink or was it understood to be about actual concentrated vinegar used as torture and then the Roman soldiers somewhat benevolently subverted the prophecy by offering the posca instead?

Notice that in this William Blake painting of the personified or pre-Fallen flea in its true form it is shown walking through black-backgrounded spaces between reddish heavy stage curtains, Blake is portraying the same limbo realm between worlds as the Black Lodge from Twin Peaks
sorry I have f.lux cranked to the max so it might be making my screen redder but in any case the colors faded so it was probably a bit more intense

Supposedly Blake was inspired to make the painting by a microscope image of a close-up flea he saw, which recalls how Goethe said microscopism modifies the character of the observed by taking it out of its intended proportion, dis-proportionality being the essence of monstrosity.

If the creature did appear to him as a ghost as claimed during a seance, it makes sense it would take a familiar monstrous shape he knew, as the aliens in Gene Wolfe who wore masks of earthly insects (or real life pseudo-extraterrestrial appearing as giant praying mantises, etc.)
One would assume the snake is not the only creature that lost its legs, similar to how Adam's eyes became unable to see angels all the time

Any single animal has an unique personality with traits like cowardice, inquisitiveness, shyness, etc. that could be expanded into a full character. Similarly how just asking an aboriginal basic questions "do you feel things change or stay the same" would sketch out a philosophy.

Like William Guppy said it every man has a perfect all-encompassing philosophy but just lacks the language to express it, similarly even individual animals do have a worldview and a rich personality even if we see a shadow of it most of the time due to a big lack of communication
